block.original:
Skǫp ōxu skjǫldunga:skyldu þeir feigir;

illa rēzk Atla,ātti þō hyggju;

feldi stoþ stōra,strīddi sēr harþla,

af bragþi boþ sendi,at kvǣmi brātt māgar.

block.translation:
Fate grew for the princes,to death they were given;

Ill counsel was Atli's,though keenness he had;

He felled his staunch bulwark,his own sorrow fashioned,

Soon a message he sentthat his kinsmen should seek him.

block.original:
Bǭru mjǫþ mǣrar,margs vas alls beini,

fōr þar fjǫlþ horna,unz vas fulldrukkit;



hiu gørþu hvīlusem þeim hø̄gst þōtti.

block.translation:
Then the famed ones brought mead,and fair was the feast,

Full many were the horns,till the men had drunk deep;



Then the mates made readytheir beds for resting.

“All women are fearful;not so do I feel,

Ill I seek not to findtill I soon must avenge it;

The king now will give usthe glow-ruddy gold;

I never shall fear,though of dangers I know.”

block.original:
“Ǫrn sāk inn fljūgaat endlǫngu hūsi:

mun oss drjūgt deilask,dreifþi oss ǫll blōþi;



hugþak af heitum,at vǣri hamr Atla.”

block.translation:
“An eagle I saw flyingfrom the end through the house,

Our fate must be bad,for with blood he sprinkled us;



From the evil I fearthat 'twas Atli's spirit.”

block.original:
“Gǫrvan sāk þēr galga,gengir at hanga,

ǣti þik ormar,yrþak þik kvikvan;



gørþisk røk ragna:rāþ hvat þat vǣri.”

block.translation:
“A gallows saw I ready,thou didst go to thy hanging,

Thy flesh serpents ate,and yet living I found thee;



The gods' doom descended;now say what it boded.”

block.original:
Snǣvarr ok Sōlarr,synir vǭru Hǫgna,

Orkning þann hētues þeim enn fylgþi,

blīþr vas bǫrr skjaldarbrōþir hans kvānar;

fōru fagrbūnar,unz þau fjǫrþr skilþi;

lǫttu ǣ ljōsar,lētuat heldr segjask.

block.translation:
Not long was it after—the end must I tell—

That the home they beheldthat Buthli once had;

Loud the gates resoundedwhen Hogni smote them;

Vingi spake then a wordthat were better unsaid:

block.original:
“A sēr þat illa,ef hafiþ āþr rāþit;

enn eruþ ōbūnir,ok hǫfum einn feldan,

lamþan til heljar:liþs vas sā yþvars.”

block.translation:
“Little it mattersif long ye have planned it;

For unarmed do ye wait,and one have we felled,

We smote him to hell,of your host was he once.”

Then wild was their angerwhen all heard his words;

Their fingers were swifton their bowstrings to seize,

Full sharply they shot,by their shields were they guarded.

block.original:
Hljōtt ǭttum sjaldan,sīz kvamt ī hendr ossar

firþan mik frǣndum,feï opt svikvinn;

senduþ systr Helju:slīks ek mest kennumk.”

block.translation:
We lay seldom togethersince to me thou wast given,

Now my kin all are gone,of my gold am I robbed;

Nay, and worst, thou didst sendmy sister to hell.”

block.original:
“Getr þū þess, Atli!gørþir svā fyrri:

mōþur tōkt mīnaok myrþir til hnossa;

svinna systrungusveltir ī helli;

hlø̄gligt þat þykkjumk,es þinn harm tīnir,

goþum þat þakkak,es þēr gengsk illa.”

block.translation:
They seized Buthli's cook,and they came with the knife,

The frightened thrall howledere the edge did he feel;

He was willing, he cried,to dung well the court yard,

Do the basest of work,if spare him they would;

Full happy were Hjalliif his life he might have.

block.original:
Hǫrpu tōk Gunnarr,hrø̄rþi ilkvistum:

slā hann svā kunni,at snōtir grētu;

klukku þeir karlar,es kunnu gørst heyra;

rīkri rǭþ sagþi,raptar sundr brustu.

block.translation:
Thus bitterly planned she,and Buthli's race threatened,

And terrible vengeanceon her husband would take;

The little ones called she,on a block she laid them;

Afraid were the proud ones,but their tears did not fall;

To their mother's arms went they,and asked what she would.

block.original:
Beiddr fōr ek heimanat biþja þīn Guþrūn!

leyfþ vastu ekkja,lētu stōrrāþa;

varþa vǭn lygi,es vēr of reyndum;

fōrtu heim hingat,fylgþi oss herr manna.

block.translation:
Not glad went I hencethy hand to seek, Guthrun,

In thy widowhood famed,but haughty men found thee;

My belief did not lie,as now we have learned;

I brought thee home hither,and a host of men with us.

block.original:
Mund galt ek mǣrri,meiþma fjǫlþ þiggja,

þrǣla þria tøgu,þȳjar sjau gōþar;

—sø̄mþ vas at slīku—:silfr vas þō meira.

block.translation:
To the famed one as bride-giftI gave jewels fair,

I gave thirty slaves,and handmaidens seven;

There was honor in such gifts,yet the silver was greater.

But all to thee wasas if nought it were worth,

While the land lay before theethat Buthli had left me;

Thou in secret didst workso the treasure I won not;

My mother full oftto sit weeping didst make,

No wedded joy found Iin fullness of heart.”

“Thou liest now, Atli,though little I heed it;

If I seldom was kindly,full cruel wast thou;

Ye brothers fought young,quarrels brought you to battle,

And half went to hellof the sons of thy house,

And all was destroyedthat should e'er have done good.

block.original:
Nār varþ þā Atli:niþjum strīþ ø̄xti;

efndi ītrborinallt þats rēþ heita;

frōþ vildi Guþrūnfara sēr at spilla:

urþu dvǫl dø̄gra,dō ī sinn annat.

block.translation:
Then did Atli die,and his heirs' grief doubled;

The high-born one didas to him she had promised;

Then sought Guthrun the wiseto go to her death,

But for days did she wait,and 'twas long ere she died.
